"# Chapter 13: Style

A bow can be solemn or cheeky. A wave can be eager or reluctant. A jump can feel jaunty, confident, or timid—and the *motion itself*—the arc, the easing, the peak—may be identical. What changes is **style**: the final axis of the 5-tuple, the lens through which timing, trajectory, easing, and embodiment are rendered.

Style is not decoration. It is the difference between a character who *moves* and a character who *feels*. It is the animator's voice, the puppet's inner life made visible. This chapter drills the `:style` parameter and the craft of rendering the same motion with different emotional color.

We will take familiar moves—a step, a turn, a bow, a leap—and author them three ways: once **neutral**, once **jaunty**, once **solemn**. Then we will compose style with weight, with timing, with secondary motion. By the end, you will be able to write a route that says \"walk, but make it wistful\" and have the sprite's gait read exactly that way.

Let's begin.

---

## The Neutral Walk

Here is a walk with no style applied—a functional loop, steady tempo, no affect:

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 100 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((step 0))
    (when (< step 60)
      (entity/move! hero 2 0)
      (entity/sprite! hero 
        (if (even? (quotient step 10)) 'girl/walk-left 'girl/walk-right))
      (world/step)
      (loop (+ step 1)))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite walks in place at a steady 2 px/frame, switching walk sprites every 10 frames. Flat, mechanical.]

The motion is correct but lifeless. It has rhythm but no *feel*. Let's add style.

---

## The Jaunty Walk

A jaunty walk is buoyant—quick tempo, slight vertical bounce, a hint of eagerness. We tighten the timing, add a small sine-wave lift, and use a slightly faster sprite cadence:

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 100 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((step 0))
    (when (< step 60)
      (let* ((base-y 300)
             (bounce (* 6 (dsin (* step 0.4))))
             (new-y (- base-y bounce)))
        (entity/set-pos! hero (+ 100 (* step 2.5)) new-y)
        (entity/sprite! hero 
          (if (even? (quotient step 8)) 'girl/walk-left 'girl/walk-right))
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ step 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite bounces lightly as she walks, each step lifting her a few pixels. The cadence is quicker. She reads as cheerful, eager.]

The math is simple—a sine wave on Y, a slightly faster horizontal speed, a tighter sprite swap—but the *feel* changes entirely. This is jaunty.

---

## The Solemn Walk

A solemn walk is heavy, slow, deliberate. We lengthen the timing, reduce the speed, and remove all vertical lift. The sprite changes less frequently, lingering in each pose:

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 100 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((step 0))
    (when (< step 60)
      (entity/move! hero 1 0)
      (entity/sprite! hero 
        (if (even? (quotient step 15)) 'girl/walk-left 'girl/walk-right))
      (world/step)
      (loop (+ step 1)))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite walks slowly, no bounce, feet planted. Each step lingers. She reads as weary, pensive, heavy-hearted.]

Same walk—different tempo, different weight, different feel. That is style.

---

## The Style Parameter

We can factor style into a parameter that governs tempo, amplitude, and easing. Here is a helper that interprets a style keyword:

```scheme
(define (style->tempo style)
  (cond
    ((eq? style 'jaunty) 0.8)
    ((eq? style 'neutral) 1.0)
    ((eq? style 'solemn) 1.5)
    (else 1.0)))

(define (style->bounce style)
  (cond
    ((eq? style 'jaunty) 8)
    ((eq? style 'neutral) 2)
    ((eq? style 'solemn) 0)
    (else 2)))

(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 100 300))
      (style 'jaunty))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let* ((tempo (style->tempo style))
         (bounce-amp (style->bounce style)))
    (let loop ((step 0))
      (when (< step 60)
        (let* ((t (* step tempo))
               (bounce (* bounce-amp (dsin (* t 0.4))))
               (new-y (- 300 bounce)))
          (entity/set-pos! hero (+ 100 (* step 2)) new-y)
          (entity/sprite! hero 
            (if (even? (quotient step 10)) 'girl/walk-left 'girl/walk-right))
          (world/step)
          (loop (+ step 1)))))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite walks with jaunty bounce. Changing the `style` binding to `'solemn` or `'neutral` would instantly re-flavor the walk.]

Now we can change the style by changing a single symbol. This is the beginning of a style system.

---

## A Bow, Three Ways

A bow is a common gesture. Here it is, neutral:

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (world/step)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 30)
      (entity/sprite! hero 
        (cond
          ((< frame 15) 'girl/bow-down)
          (else 'girl/bow-up)))
      (world/step)
      (loop (+ frame 1)))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite bows—sprite shifts from stand to bow-down for 15 frames, then bow-up for 15. Neutral timing, no affect.]

Now, **jaunty**: quick tempo, a little overshoot, a bounce at the end:

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (world/step)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 24)
      (let* ((t (/ frame 24.0))
             (bow-phase (cond
                          ((< t 0.4) 'girl/bow-down)
                          ((< t 0.6) 'girl/bow-down)
                          (else 'girl/bow-up)))
             (y-offset (if (> frame 20) (* 2 (dsin (* (- frame 20) 1.5))) 0)))
        (entity/set-pos! hero 200 (- 300 y-offset))
        (entity/sprite! hero bow-phase)
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite bows quickly, rises, and bounces slightly at the end—eager, friendly, a little theatrical.]

And **solemn**: slow, held at the bottom, no bounce, a long rise:

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (world/step)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 50)
      (entity/sprite! hero 
        (cond
          ((< frame 15) 'girl/bow-down)
          ((< frame 35) 'girl/bow-down)
          (else 'girl/bow-up)))
      (world/step)
      (loop (+ frame 1)))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite bows slowly, holds at the bottom for 20 frames, rises slowly. Grave, reverent.]

Same gesture. Three emotional colors.

---

## A Jump, Styled

Here is a neutral jump—functional arc, no affect:

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 40)
      (let* ((t (/ frame 40.0))
             (arc (* 80 (- (* 4 t) (* 4 t t))))
             (new-y (- 300 arc)))
        (entity/set-pos! hero 200 new-y)
        (entity/sprite! hero 
          (cond
            ((< frame 10) 'girl/crouch)
            ((< frame 30) 'girl/jump)
            (else 'girl/stand)))
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite jumps—parabolic arc, neutral timing.]

Now, **jaunty**: quick anticipation, high peak, fast rise, little settle bounce:

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 35)
      (let* ((t (/ frame 35.0))
             (arc (* 100 (- (* 4 t) (* 4 t t))))
             (settle (if (> frame 30) (* 2 (dsin (* (- frame 30) 2))) 0))
             (new-y (- 300 arc settle)))
        (entity/set-pos! hero 200 new-y)
        (entity/sprite! hero 
          (cond
            ((< frame 5) 'girl/crouch)
            ((< frame 28) 'girl/jump)
            (else 'girl/stand)))
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite jumps eagerly—quick crouch, high arc, little bounce on landing. Reads as excited, playful.]

And **solemn**: slow anticipation, lower peak, heavy settle, no bounce:

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 60)
      (let* ((t (/ frame 60.0))
             (arc (* 50 (- (* 4 t) (* 4 t t))))
             (new-y (- 300 arc)))
        (entity/set-pos! hero 200 new-y)
        (entity/sprite! hero 
          (cond
            ((< frame 15) 'girl/crouch)
            ((< frame 45) 'girl/jump)
            (else 'girl/stand)))
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite jumps slowly, peak lower, lingers in the air, lands with weight. Reads as reluctant, heavy-hearted.]

Three jumps. Same parabola, different feel.

---

## Style and Easing

Easing curves (ease-in, ease-out, ease-in-out) are **neutral** transforms—they shape a motion's arrival without imposing affect. But the *choice* of easing, and how sharply it's applied, can amplify style.

Here is a move with neutral easing (linear):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 100 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 40)
      (let* ((t (/ frame 40.0))
             (new-x (+ 100 (* t 200))))
        (entity/set-pos! hero new-x 300)
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite slides from x=100 to x=300, constant speed. Flat, robotic.]

Now with **ease-out** (sharp deceleration—jaunty arrival):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 100 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 40)
      (let* ((t (/ frame 40.0))
             (ease-t (- 1 (* (- 1 t) (- 1 t))))
             (new-x (+ 100 (* ease-t 200))))
        (entity/set-pos! hero new-x 300)
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite zips to the right, decelerates sharply at the end. Reads as eager, confident.]

And with **ease-in-out** (symmetrical, solemn):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 100 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 40)
      (let* ((t (/ frame 40.0))
             (ease-t (if (< t 0.5)
                         (* 2 t t)
                         (- 1 (* 2 (- 1 t) (- 1 t)))))
             (new-x (+ 100 (* ease-t 200))))
        (entity/set-pos! hero new-x 300)
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite accelerates smoothly, decelerates symmetrically. Reads as measured, deliberate.]

Easing + style = feel.

---

## Style and Oscillation

Oscillation (sine/cosine) is the engine of sway, breathe, idle. The amplitude, frequency, and phase offset can encode style.

**Neutral idle sway**:

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 120)
      (let* ((sway (* 4 (dsin (* frame 0.05))))
             (new-x (+ 200 sway)))
        (entity/set-pos! hero new-x 300)
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite sways gently side-to-side, small amplitude, slow frequency. Calm, neutral.]

**Jaunty idle sway** (faster, larger amplitude, head-bob):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 120)
      (let* ((sway (* 8 (dsin (* frame 0.1))))
             (bob (* 3 (dsin (* frame 0.15))))
             (new-x (+ 200 sway))
             (new-y (- 300 bob)))
        (entity/set-pos! hero new-x new-y)
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite sways side-to-side with larger amplitude, plus a little vertical bob. Reads as restless, eager, can't-stand-still.]

**Solemn idle** (barely perceptible sway, very slow):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 120)
      (let* ((sway (* 2 (dsin (* frame 0.025))))
             (new-x (+ 200 sway)))
        (entity/set-pos! hero new-x 300)
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite sways almost imperceptibly, very slow, tiny amplitude. Reads as still, contemplative, heavy.]

Three idle loops. Three moods.

---

## Style and Secondary Motion

Secondary motion—follow-through, drag, overshoot—amplifies style. A jaunty character's hair lags with high amplitude and quick settle. A solemn character's hair barely moves.

**Neutral step with hair follow-through**:

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300))
      (hair-x 200)
      (hair-y 280))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 60)
      (let* ((body-x (+ 200 (* frame 2)))
             (dx (- body-x hair-x))
             (hair-vx (* dx 0.1)))
        (set! hair-x (+ hair-x hair-vx))
        (entity/set-pos! hero body-x 300)
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite walks; her \"hair\" (a trailing point) follows with slight lag. Neutral lag constant.]

**Jaunty** (high lag, overshoot):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300))
      (hair-x 200)
      (hair-vx 0))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 60)
      (let* ((body-x (+ 200 (* frame 2.5)))
             (dx (- body-x hair-x))
             (accel (* dx 0.15)))
        (set! hair-vx (+ hair-vx accel))
        (set! hair-vx (* hair-vx 0.85))
        (set! hair-x (+ hair-x hair-vx))
        (entity/set-pos! hero body-x 300)
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite's hair lags significantly, bounces past the target, settles with spring. Reads as lively, energetic.]

**Solemn** (minimal lag, heavy damping):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300))
      (hair-x 200))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 60)
      (let* ((body-x (+ 200 (* frame 1)))
             (dx (- body-x hair-x))
             (hair-vx (* dx 0.05)))
        (set! hair-x (+ hair-x hair-vx))
        (entity/set-pos! hero body-x 300)
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite's hair follows closely, almost no lag, no overshoot. Reads as heavy, subdued.]

Style is in the parameters of the secondary motion system.

---

## A Wave, Styled

A wave is a multi-part gesture: raise arm, hold, lower, with hand oscillation. Here it is neutral:

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300))
      (arm-angle 0))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 60)
      (set! arm-angle 
        (cond
          ((< frame 15) (* (/ frame 15.0) 90))
          ((< frame 45) 90)
          (else (* (- 1 (/ (- frame 45) 15.0)) 90))))
      (world/step)
      (loop (+ frame 1)))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite raises her arm (angle 0→90 over 15 frames), holds for 30, lowers over 15. Neutral timing.]

**Jaunty wave** (quick raise, wiggle at the top, bounce down):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300))
      (arm-angle 0))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 50)
      (let* ((wiggle (if (and (>= frame 10) (< frame 40))
                         (* 10 (dsin (* (- frame 10) 0.6)))
                         0)))
        (set! arm-angle 
          (cond
            ((< frame 10) (* (/ frame 10.0) 90))
            ((< frame 40) (+ 90 wiggle))
            (else (* (- 1 (/ (- frame 40) 10.0)) 90))))
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite's arm shoots up quickly, wiggles side-to-side at the top (eager wave), drops quickly. Reads as friendly, enthusiastic.]

**Solemn wave** (slow raise, long hold, no wiggle, slow lower):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300))
      (arm-angle 0))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 80)
      (set! arm-angle 
        (cond
          ((< frame 20) (* (/ frame 20.0) 70))
          ((< frame 60) 70)
          (else (* (- 1 (/ (- frame 60) 20.0)) 70))))
      (world/step)
      (loop (+ frame 1)))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite raises her arm slowly to a lower angle (70° instead of 90°), holds for 40 frames, lowers slowly. Reads as reluctant, formal, goodbye-not-hello.]

Same gesture, three farewells.

---

## Style and Anticipation

Anticipation—the windup before an action—can be quick (jaunty) or slow (solemn). Here is a neutral toss (slight crouch, then throw):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300))
      (ball (world/spawn 'ball 200 260)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (entity/sprite! ball 'ball)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 50)
      (cond
        ((< frame 10)
         (entity/set-pos! hero 200 (+ 300 (* frame 1.5))))
        ((< frame 15)
         (entity/set-pos! hero 200 315))
        ((< frame 20)
         (entity/set-pos! hero 200 (- 315 (* (- frame 15) 3)))))
      (when (>= frame 20)
        (let* ((t (- frame 20))
               (vx 3)
               (vy -8)
               (ball-x (+ 200 (* t vx)))
               (ball-y (+ 260 (* t vy) (* 0.3 t t))))
          (entity/set-pos! ball ball-x ball-y)))
      (world/step)
      (loop (+ frame 1)))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite crouches slightly (10 frames), holds briefly, rises and releases the ball in a parabolic arc. Neutral timing.]

**Jaunty toss** (quick crouch, overshoot, fast release):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300))
      (ball (world/spawn 'ball 200 260)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (entity/sprite! ball 'ball)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 45)
      (cond
        ((< frame 6)
         (entity/set-pos! hero 200 (+ 300 (* frame 2.5))))
        ((< frame 10)
         (entity/set-pos! hero 200 (- 315 (* (- frame 6) 3.75)))))
      (when (>= frame 10)
        (let* ((t (- frame 10))
               (vx 4)
               (vy -10)
               (ball-x (+ 200 (* t vx)))
               (ball-y (+ 260 (* t vy) (* 0.35 t t))))
          (entity/set-pos! ball ball-x ball-y)))
      (world/step)
      (loop (+ frame 1)))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite crouches fast and deep, springs up, releases the ball with higher velocity. Reads as energetic, playful throw.]

**Solemn toss** (slow crouch, long hold, gentle release):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300))
      (ball (world/spawn 'ball 200 260)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (entity/sprite! ball 'ball)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 70)
      (cond
        ((< frame 20)
         (entity/set-pos! hero 200 (+ 300 (* frame 0.75))))
        ((< frame 35)
         (entity/set-pos! hero 200 315))
        ((< frame 45)
         (entity/set-pos! hero 200 (- 315 (* (- frame 35) 1.5)))))
      (when (>= frame 45)
        (let* ((t (- frame 45))
               (vx 2)
               (vy -5)
               (ball-x (+ 200 (* t vx)))
               (ball-y (+ 260 (* t vy) (* 0.25 t t))))
          (entity/set-pos! ball ball-x ball-y)))
      (world/step)
      (loop (+ frame 1)))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite crouches slowly, holds for 15 frames, rises slowly, releases the ball gently with low velocity. Reads as reluctant, careful, perhaps tossing something precious.]

Anticipation timing = emotional setup.

---

## Style and Weight

Weight (from Chapter 6) is an embodiment parameter—but the *perception* of weight is amplified by style. A jaunty character can feel light even with heavy gravity; a solemn character can feel heavy even with low mass. Style and weight interlock.

**Heavy ball, jaunty bounce**:

```scheme
(let ((ball (world/spawn 'ball 200 100)))
  (entity/sprite! ball 'ball)
  (entity/set-vel! ball 0 0)
  (entity/gravity-scale! ball 1.2)
  (entity/bounce! ball 0.7)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 120)
      (let* ((pos-y (entity/y ball)))
        (when (and (>= pos-y 300) (< (entity/y ball) 305))
          (entity/accel! ball 0 (* -3 (dsin (* frame 0.8)))))
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: Ball falls with heavy gravity, bounces with high restitution, little squash added at impact. Reads as a rubber ball—heavy but playful.]

**Same ball, solemn drop** (low bounce, long settle):

```scheme
(let ((ball (world/spawn 'ball 200 100)))
  (entity/sprite! ball 'ball)
  (entity/set-vel! ball 0 0)
  (entity/gravity-scale! ball 1.2)
  (entity/bounce! ball 0.3)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 120)
      (world/step)
      (loop (+ frame 1)))))
```

[VISUAL: Ball falls, bounces weakly, settles quickly. Reads as a lead weight, heavy, no playfulness.]

Same mass, different style.

---

## Style Across a Phrase

A motion *phrase* is a sequence of moves—walk, stop, turn, wave, walk again. Style should be consistent across the phrase. Here is a neutral phrase:

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 100 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 120)
      (cond
        ((< frame 40)
         (entity/move! hero 2 0))
        ((< frame 60)
         (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand))
        ((< frame 80)
         (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/wave))
        (else
         (entity/move! hero 2 0)))
      (world/step)
      (loop (+ frame 1)))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite walks 40 frames, stops and stands for 20, waves for 20, walks again. Neutral, flat timing.]

Now, **jaunty phrase**: quick walk with bounce, snap to stop, eager wave, quick resume:

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 100 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 100)
      (cond
        ((< frame 30)
         (let* ((bounce (* 4 (dsin (* frame 0.5))))
                (new-y (- 300 bounce)))
           (entity/set-pos! hero (+ 100 (* frame 2.5)) new-y)))
        ((< frame 35)
         (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand))
        ((< frame 55)
         (let* ((wiggle (* 8 (dsin (* (- frame 35) 0.6)))))
           (entity/set-pos! hero (+ (entity/x hero) (* wiggle 0.05)) 300)
           (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/wave)))
        (else
         (let* ((bounce (* 4 (dsin (* frame 0.5))))
                (new-y (- 300 bounce)))
           (entity/set-pos! hero (+ (entity/x hero) 2.5) new-y))))
      (world/step)
      (loop (+ frame 1)))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite bounces while walking, stops quickly, waves with side-to-side wiggle, resumes bouncy walk. Reads as cheerful, energetic throughout.]

**Solemn phrase**: slow walk, long stop, slow wave, slow resume:

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 100 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 160)
      (cond
        ((< frame 50)
         (entity/move! hero 1 0))
        ((< frame 80)
         (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand))
        ((< frame 120)
         (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/wave))
        (else
         (entity/move! hero 1 0)))
      (world/step)
      (loop (+ frame 1)))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite walks slowly, stops and stands for 30 frames, waves slowly (no wiggle), resumes slow walk. Reads as weary, contemplative throughout.]

Style binds a phrase into a coherent performance.

---

## Parametric Style Control

We can build a style interpolator—blend from solemn to jaunty via a 0..1 parameter:

```scheme
(define (style-mix s)
  (let ((tempo (+ 1.5 (* s -0.7)))
        (bounce (* s 8))
        (speed (+ 1 (* s 1.5))))
    (list tempo bounce speed)))

(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 100 300))
      (style-param 0.5))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let* ((params (style-mix style-param))
         (tempo (car params))
         (bounce (cadr params))
         (speed (caddr params)))
    (let loop ((frame 0))
      (when (< frame 60)
        (let* ((t (* frame tempo))
               (y-bounce (* bounce (dsin (* t 0.4))))
               (new-y (- 300 y-bounce)))
          (entity/set-pos! hero (+ 100 (* frame speed)) new-y)
          (world/step)
          (loop (+ frame 1)))))))
```

[VISUAL: With `style-param` at 0.5, the sprite walks at moderate tempo and bounce—halfway between solemn and jaunty. Changing the param slides the style.]

Now you can author a route that says `(walk-with-style 0.8)` and get a motion 80% jaunty, 20% solemn.

---

## Style and Expression

Expression (from Chapter 11) is composed with style. A nod can be eager or reluctant. Here is a neutral nod:

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0) (angle 0))
    (when (< frame 40)
      (let* ((new-angle 
               (cond
                 ((< frame 10) (* (/ frame 10.0) 20))
                 ((< frame 20) 20)
                 ((< frame 30) (* (- 1 (/ (- frame 20) 10.0)) 20))
                 (else 0))))
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1) new-angle)))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite's head tilts forward 20° over 10 frames, holds for 10, returns over 10, holds at 0. Neutral nod.]

**Eager nod** (fast down, overshoot, quick return):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0) (angle 0))
    (when (< frame 30)
      (let* ((new-angle 
               (cond
                 ((< frame 6) (* (/ frame 6.0) 25))
                 ((< frame 10) (+ 25 (* (- frame 6) -1.25)))
                 ((< frame 20) 20)
                 (else (* (- 1 (/ (- frame 20) 10.0)) 20)))))
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1) new-angle)))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite's head drops quickly to 25°, overshoots to 20°, holds briefly, snaps back up. Reads as enthusiastic \"yes!\".]

**Reluctant nod** (slow down, long hold, slow return):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0) (angle 0))
    (when (< frame 60)
      (let* ((new-angle 
               (cond
                 ((< frame 20) (* (/ frame 20.0) 15))
                 ((< frame 45) 15)
                 (else (* (- 1 (/ (- frame 45) 15.0)) 15)))))
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1) new-angle)))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite's head tilts slowly to a shallow 15°, holds for 25 frames, rises slowly. Reads as reluctant agreement, \"I guess…\".]

Expression + style = subtext.

---

## Style in Gait

Gait (from Chapter 10) is locomotion style. A walk can be a trudge, a bounce, a slink. Here are three gaits, same step function, different parameters:

**Trudge** (heavy, slow, low lift):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 100 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((step 0))
    (when (< step 60)
      (let* ((lift (if (< (modulo step 20) 10) 2 0))
             (new-y (- 300 lift)))
        (entity/set-pos! hero (+ 100 (* step 1.2)) new-y)
        (entity/sprite! hero 
          (if (even? (quotient step 10)) 'girl/walk-left 'girl/walk-right))
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ step 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite walks slowly, feet barely lift, slow cadence. Reads as exhausted trudge.]

**Bounce** (high lift, quick tempo):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 100 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((step 0))
    (when (< step 60)
      (let* ((lift (* 8 (abs (dsin (* step 0.4)))))
             (new-y (- 300 lift)))
        (entity/set-pos! hero (+ 100 (* step 2.5)) new-y)
        (entity/sprite! hero 
          (if (even? (quotient step 7)) 'girl/walk-left 'girl/walk-right))
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ step 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite bounces with every step, high lift, fast forward speed. Reads as skipping, joyful gait.]

**Slink** (low posture, smooth, side-to-side sway):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 100 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((step 0))
    (when (< step 60)
      (let* ((sway (* 5 (dsin (* step 0.3))))
             (new-x (+ 100 (* step 1.5) sway))
             (new-y (+ 300 3)))
        (entity/set-pos! hero new-x new-y)
        (entity/sprite! hero 
          (if (even? (quotient step 12)) 'girl/walk-left 'girl/walk-right))
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ step 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite walks with a low crouch, side-to-side sway, slow tempo. Reads as sneaking, cautious gait.]

Three gaits, three attitudes.

---

## Style and Camera

Camera motion (Chapter 16) can also carry style. A jaunty camera leads slightly, anticipates the action. A solemn camera follows at a distance, passive. Here is a neutral camera follow:

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 100 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (world/camera-follow! hero 0.1)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 120)
      (entity/move! hero 2 0)
      (world/step)
      (loop (+ frame 1)))))
```

[VISUAL: Camera follows the sprite with a 0.1 damping constant—smooth, neutral tracking.]

**Jaunty camera** (leads slightly, quick catch-up):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 100 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (world/camera-follow! hero 0.2)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 120)
      (entity/move! hero 2.5 0)
      (world/step)
      (loop (+ frame 1)))))
```

[VISUAL: Camera follows the sprite more eagerly (higher damping = faster catch-up), slightly ahead of her. Reads as energetic, anticipatory camera.]

**Solemn camera** (lags, slow catch-up):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 100 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (world/camera-follow! hero 0.05)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 120)
      (entity/move! hero 1 0)
      (world/step)
      (loop (+ frame 1)))))
```

[VISUAL: Camera follows the sprite slowly (low damping), lags behind. Reads as contemplative, observational camera.]

Camera style supports character style.

---

## Style and Settle

Settle (how a motion comes to rest) is a style signal. Jaunty settle has overshoot and bounce. Solemn settle is damped, no overshoot.

**Jaunty settle** (spring to target):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 100 300))
      (target-x 300)
      (vx 0))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0) (x 100) (vel vx))
    (when (< frame 120)
      (let* ((dx (- target-x x))
             (accel (* dx 0.08))
             (new-vel (+ vel accel))
             (damped-vel (* new-vel 0.92))
             (new-x (+ x damped-vel)))
        (entity/set-pos! hero new-x 300)
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1) new-x damped-vel)))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite springs toward x=300, overshoots, bounces back, settles with oscillation. Reads as eager arrival.]

**Solemn settle** (critically damped, no overshoot):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 100 300))
      (target-x 300)
      (vx 0))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0) (x 100) (vel vx))
    (when (< frame 120)
      (let* ((dx (- target-x x))
             (accel (* dx 0.05))
             (new-vel (+ vel accel))
             (damped-vel (* new-vel 0.7))
             (new-x (+ x damped-vel)))
        (entity/set-pos! hero new-x 300)
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1) new-x damped-vel)))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite glides toward x=300, decelerates smoothly, arrives with no overshoot. Reads as measured, deliberate arrival.]

Settle style = arrival personality.

---

## A Turn, Styled

A turn (rotate in place) can be quick-snap (jaunty) or slow-pivot (solemn). Here is neutral:

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300))
      (angle 0))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 40)
      (let* ((target 180)
             (new-angle (+ angle (* (- target angle) 0.1))))
        (set! angle new-angle)
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite rotates from 0° to 180° with exponential ease-out. Neutral timing.]

**Jaunty turn** (fast, overshoot, snap back):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300))
      (angle 0)
      (vel 0))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 30)
      (let* ((target 180)
             (accel (* (- target angle) 0.15))
             (new-vel (+ vel accel))
             (damped-vel (* new-vel 0.9))
             (new-angle (+ angle damped-vel)))
        (set! vel damped-vel)
        (set! angle new-angle)
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite spins quickly to 180°, overshoots slightly, snaps back. Reads as quick reaction, eager pivot.]

**Solemn turn** (slow, no overshoot, long ease-in-out):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300))
      (angle 0))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 60)
      (let* ((t (/ frame 60.0))
             (ease-t (if (< t 0.5)
                         (* 2 t t)
                         (- 1 (* 2 (- 1 t) (- 1 t)))))
             (new-angle (* ease-t 180)))
        (set! angle new-angle)
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite rotates slowly from 0° to 180° over 60 frames, ease-in-out, no overshoot. Reads as deliberate, careful turn.]

Turn style = intention.

---

## Style in Reaction

Reaction timing (how quickly a character responds to stimulus) is a style parameter. Jaunty = instant. Solemn = delayed.

**Jaunty reaction** (ball appears, instant chase):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 100 300))
      (ball (world/spawn 'ball 300 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (entity/sprite! ball 'ball)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 60)
      (when (>= frame 10)
        (let* ((ball-x (entity/x ball))
               (hero-x (entity/x hero))
               (dx (- ball-x hero-x))
               (move-x (if (> (abs dx) 5) (* (/ dx (abs dx)) 3) 0)))
          (entity/move! hero move-x 0)))
      (world/step)
      (loop (+ frame 1)))))
```

[VISUAL: Ball spawns at x=300. The sprite instantly (frame 10) begins moving toward it at speed 3. Reads as eager, alert.]

**Solemn reaction** (ball appears, delayed response, slow approach):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 100 300))
      (ball (world/spawn 'ball 300 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (entity/sprite! ball 'ball)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 80)
      (when (>= frame 30)
        (let* ((ball-x (entity/x ball))
               (hero-x (entity/x hero))
               (dx (- ball-x hero-x))
               (move-x (if (> (abs dx) 5) (* (/ dx (abs dx)) 1) 0)))
          (entity/move! hero move-x 0)))
      (world/step)
      (loop (+ frame 1)))))
```

[VISUAL: Ball spawns at x=300. The sprite waits until frame 30, then slowly moves toward it at speed 1. Reads as reluctant, hesitant.]

Reaction delay = emotional state.

---

## A Phrase with Mixed Styles

Sometimes a character's style *changes* mid-scene—starts solemn, becomes jaunty as mood lifts. Here is a walk that transitions from solemn to jaunty:

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 100 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 120)
      (let* ((style-t (/ frame 120.0))
             (tempo (+ 1.5 (* style-t -0.7)))
             (bounce (* style-t 8))
             (speed (+ 1 (* style-t 1.5)))
             (y-bounce (* bounce (dsin (* frame 0.4))))
             (new-y (- 300 y-bounce)))
        (entity/set-pos! hero (+ 100 (* frame speed)) new-y)
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite starts walking slowly with no bounce (solemn). As she walks, tempo increases, bounce appears, speed rises. By frame 120 she's bouncy and fast (jaunty). Reads as mood lifting, energy returning.]

Style as a *narrative arc* within a phrase.

---

## Style as a Character Trait

Different characters can have *default* styles—one character is always jaunty, another always solemn. Here are two characters walking side-by-side:

```scheme
(let ((jaunty-girl (world/spawn 'girl 100 300))
      (solemn-girl (world/spawn 'girl 100 320)))
  (entity/sprite! jaunty-girl 'girl/stand)
  (entity/sprite! solemn-girl 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 120)
      (let* ((jaunty-bounce (* 6 (dsin (* frame 0.5))))
             (jaunty-y (- 300 jaunty-bounce))
             (jaunty-x (+ 100 (* frame 2.5))))
        (entity/set-pos! jaunty-girl jaunty-x jaunty-y))
      (let* ((solemn-x (+ 100 (* frame 1))))
        (entity/set-pos! solemn-girl solemn-x 320))
      (world/step)
      (loop (+ frame 1)))))
```

[VISUAL: Two girls walk side-by-side. Top girl bounces with jaunty gait. Bottom girl walks slowly, no bounce, solemn. Their styles contrast, read as different personalities.]

Style = character identity.

---

## Style and Squash/Stretch

Squash and stretch (Chapter 7) amplify style. Jaunty squash is exaggerated, fast. Solemn squash is minimal, slow.

**Jaunty bounce with heavy squash**:

```scheme
(let ((ball (world/spawn 'ball 200 100)))
  (entity/sprite! ball 'ball)
  (entity/set-vel! ball 0 0)
  (entity/gravity-scale! ball 0.8)
  (entity/bounce! ball 0.9)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 120)
      (let* ((vy (cadr (entity/vel ball)))
             (on-ground (>= (entity/y ball) 300))
             (squash-y (if (and on-ground (< vy 0.5)) 0.6 1.0))
             (squash-x (/ 1.0 squash-y)))
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: Ball bounces, squashes heavily on impact (60% height, wider), springs back. Reads as playful, elastic, jaunty bounce.]

**Solemn drop with minimal squash**:

```scheme
(let ((ball (world/spawn 'ball 200 100)))
  (entity/sprite! ball 'ball)
  (entity/set-vel! ball 0 0)
  (entity/gravity-scale! ball 1.0)
  (entity/bounce! ball 0.2)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 120)
      (let* ((vy (cadr (entity/vel ball)))
             (on-ground (>= (entity/y ball) 300))
             (squash-y (if (and on-ground (< vy 0.5)) 0.9 1.0))
             (squash-x (/ 1.0 squash-y)))
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: Ball drops, barely squashes on impact (90% height), minimal bounce. Reads as heavy, solemn, a leaden weight.]

Squash/stretch magnitude = style amplifier.

---

## Style in a Chase

A chase can be frantic (jaunty) or methodical (solemn). Here is a neutral chase:

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 100 300))
      (target (world/spawn 'ball 300 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (entity/sprite! target 'ball)
  (entity/set-vel! target -2 0)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 120)
      (let* ((dx (- (entity/x target) (entity/x hero)))
             (move-x (if (> (abs dx) 10) (* (/ dx (abs dx)) 2.5) 0)))
        (entity/move! hero move-x 0)
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: Ball moves left at speed 2. The sprite chases at speed 2.5. Neutral timing, steady pursuit.]

**Frantic chase** (fast, bouncy, overshoot):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 100 300))
      (target (world/spawn 'ball 300 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (entity/sprite! target 'ball)
  (entity/set-vel! target -3 0)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 100)
      (let* ((dx (- (entity/x target) (entity/x hero)))
             (move-x (* (/ dx (abs dx)) 4))
             (bounce (* 6 (dsin (* frame 0.6))))
             (new-y (- 300 bounce)))
        (entity/move! hero move-x 0)
        (entity/set-pos! hero (entity/x hero) new-y)
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: Ball flees quickly. The sprite chases with high speed, bouncing frantically. Reads as urgent, desperate chase.]

**Methodical chase** (slow, steady, relentless):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 100 300))
      (target (world/spawn 'ball 300 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (entity/sprite! target 'ball)
  (entity/set-vel! target -1 0)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 150)
      (let* ((dx (- (entity/x target) (entity/x hero)))
             (move-x (if (> (abs dx) 5) (* (/ dx (abs dx)) 1.2) 0)))
        (entity/move! hero move-x 0)
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: Ball moves slowly. The sprite follows at steady slow pace, no bounce, relentless. Reads as patient, inevitable pursuit.]

Chase style = urgency vs patience.

---

## Style in an Idle Loop

Idle animations (what a character does while waiting) are style showcases. Here are three idle loops:

**Jaunty idle** (bounce, sway, restless):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 180)
      (let* ((sway (* 6 (dsin (* frame 0.1))))
             (bounce (* 3 (dsin (* frame 0.15))))
             (new-x (+ 200 sway))
             (new-y (- 300 bounce)))
        (entity/set-pos! hero new-x new-y)
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite sways side-to-side, bounces slightly, can't stand still. Reads as eager, energetic, impatient.]

**Neutral idle** (slow breathe, minimal sway):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 180)
      (let* ((breathe (* 1 (dsin (* frame 0.05))))
             (new-y (- 300 breathe)))
        (entity/set-pos! hero 200 new-y)
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite breathes gently (small vertical sine), no horizontal motion. Reads as calm, at rest.]

**Solemn idle** (almost still, very slow sway):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 180)
      (let* ((sway (* 1.5 (dsin (* frame 0.02))))
             (new-x (+ 200 sway)))
        (entity/set-pos! hero new-x 300)
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite sways imperceptibly, very slow frequency, tiny amplitude. Reads as still, contemplative, heavy.]

Idle = baseline style.

---

## Style in Departure

A departure (leaving the scene) can be reluctant (solemn) or eager (jaunty). Neutral departure:

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 60)
      (entity/move! hero 2 0)
      (world/step)
      (loop (+ frame 1)))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite walks steadily off-screen to the right. Neutral speed, no affect.]

**Eager departure** (quick, bouncy, accelerating):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 50)
      (let* ((speed (+ 2 (* frame 0.05)))
             (bounce (* 5 (dsin (* frame 0.6))))
             (new-y (- 300 bounce)))
        (entity/move! hero speed 0)
        (entity/set-pos! hero (entity/x hero) new-y)
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite walks off-screen, accelerating, bouncing. Reads as eager to leave, excited about what's next.]

**Reluctant departure** (slow, pauses, glances back):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl 200 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 100)
      (let* ((move? (or (< frame 20) (and (> frame 40) (< frame 60)) (> frame 80)))
             (speed (if move? 1 0)))
        (entity/move! hero speed 0)
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1))))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite walks a few steps, stops, stands still (pauses, as if looking back), walks again, stops. Reads as reluctant to leave, conflicted.]

Departure style = narrative subtext.

---

## Style in Arrival

Arrival is the inverse—how a character enters. Jaunty = burst in. Solemn = slow entrance.

**Jaunty arrival** (fast entrance, skid to a stop, overshoot):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl -50 300))
      (vx 5))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0) (vel vx))
    (when (< frame 60)
      (let* ((target-x 200)
             (x (entity/x hero))
             (past-target (> x target-x))
             (new-vel (if past-target (* vel 0.85) vel))
             (bounce (if (and past-target (< (abs new-vel) 0.5)) 
                         (* 3 (dsin (* frame 1.5))) 
                         0)))
        (entity/move! hero new-vel 0)
        (entity/set-pos! hero (entity/x hero) (- 300 bounce))
        (world/step)
        (loop (+ frame 1) new-vel)))))
```

[VISUAL: The sprite zooms in from left at high speed, overshoots x=200, skids back, settles with a little bounce. Reads as energetic arrival, \"I'm here!\".]

**Solemn arrival** (slow walk-on, no rush):

```scheme
(let ((hero (world/spawn 'girl -50 300)))
  (entity/sprite! hero 'girl/stand)
  (let loop ((frame 0))
    (when (< frame 120)
      (let* ((x (entity/x hero))
             (target-x 200)
             (dx (- target-x x))
             (speed (if (> (abs dx) 5) 1.2 0)))


---

## Notes and Additional Considerations from r1 draft

*The following material comes from an earlier or parallel revision draft (r1 draft). It is preserved here because content costs thought — nothing gets thrown away. Some passages restate the chapter's core ideas in a different voice; others introduce examples or angles not covered above. Read as supplemental exercises for the same discipline.*

### 13.1 Speed Signature

Two characters cross the same distance. One is always in a hurry.

```scheme
;; Hurried crossing — short duration, no pause
(motion
  (take 0.4
    (ease-out
      (shift (vec 0 0) (vec 160 0)))))
```

[VISUAL: circle zips left-to-right, brief ease-out, arrives quickly]

```scheme
;; Unhurried crossing — long duration, gentle ease
(motion
  (take 2.0
    (ease-in-out
      (shift (vec 0 0) (vec 160 0)))))
```

[VISUAL: circle drifts left-to-right, slow ease, lingers in transitions]

Same distance, same easing family — the duration alone speaks volumes.

---


### 13.2 Arc Personality

A reach can be direct or searching.

```scheme
;; Direct reach — minimal arc, shortest path
(motion
  (take 0.5
    (along-arc
      (vec 0 0) (vec 100 60)
      (control (vec 20 10)))))
```

[VISUAL: arm extends nearly straight, small bulge, confident arrival]

```scheme
;; Hesitant reach — exaggerated arc, exploratory path
(motion
  (take 1.2
    (along-arc
      (vec 0 0) (vec 100 60)
      (control (vec 50 -30)))))
```

[VISUAL: arm sweeps upward then down, large detour, cautious arrival]

The control point bends the trajectory into intent.

---


### 13.3 Ease Disposition

Ease curves set emotional tone.

```scheme
;; Aggressive snap — ease-in, all acceleration
(motion
  (take 0.3
    (ease-in
      (shift (vec -50 0) (vec 50 0)))))
```

[VISUAL: slow start, sudden slam to finish]

```scheme
;; Gentle drift — ease-out, all deceleration
(motion
  (take 0.8
    (ease-out
      (shift (vec -50 0) (vec 50 0)))))
```

[VISUAL: quick start, slow settling]

```scheme
;; Mechanical steady — linear, no personality
(motion
  (take 0.5
    (shift (vec -50 0) (vec 50 0))))
```

[VISUAL: constant speed, robotic]

Ease is the breath of motion.

---


### 13.4 Overshoot vs. Undershoot

Does motion commit or second-guess?

```scheme
;; Confident overshoot — push past target, snap back
(motion
  (sequence
    (take 0.4
      (ease-in
        (shift (vec 0 0) (vec 110 0))))
    (take 0.15
      (ease-out
        (shift (vec 110 0) (vec 100 0))))))
```

[VISUAL: slides past mark, corrects quickly]

```scheme
;; Tentative undershoot — arrive short, creep forward
(motion
  (sequence
    (take 0.6
      (ease-out
        (shift (vec 0 0) (vec 85 0))))
    (take 0.3
      (shift (vec 85 0) (vec 100 0)))))
```

[VISUAL: stops early, inches to goal]

Overshoot reads as decisive; undershoot as cautious.

